Is it going to be a better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
Firstly, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly inadequate system to protect the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the inefficiency of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that have taken around 70 years to build.
This is why it is essential that a genuinely active approach be taken this year at the European and global levels.
Next September, United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit to build a solid global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to make a concrete and lasting commitment.
This necessary commitment was cruelly lacking last year.
Indeed, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of the crisis last year if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host at least four million refugees.
With approximately €10 billion, these countries would have been better able to accommodate, feed, and educate the refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to €21 billion every year in the future.
But the financial implications of the crisis are incomparable to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, then endured an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing them refuge.
The most cynical politicians have mercilessly exploited the fear of citizens, promoting a hateful nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the migrants' experiences.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist activities.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote their own anti-immigration policies.
This situation has significantly undermined European cooperation.
The EU's program to handle the million refugees who arrived on its shores has only allowed for the "relocation" of 190.
Border controls in six Schengen area countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today chauvinistic and incompetent.
Of course, solving this crisis is not only about Europe; responsibility cannot be defined by simple geographical proximity.
Whatever the case, the EU is likely facing a threat to its own existence today, which it can only overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That's why it is up to the member states to take the initiative in proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure pathways allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that every struggling migrant must be welcomed.
It is nonetheless up to the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to employ orderly mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
Such a system would allow for the protection of migrants while safeguarding Europe (by enabling a thorough examination of asylum requests).
Going beyond an approach aimed at dissuading asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
Equally important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will above all require more countries to agree to accept refugees.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only managed to resettle less than 75,000 out of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an average duration of estimated 25 years, trapped in a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a potential return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to agree to accept a cumulative total of nearly one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
The Canada having stated that it will welcome alone 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
At present, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed for each refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and professional training during the first years of installation.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of building or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, the water supply systems are struggling with the massive influx of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But effective migrant integration will only be possible if European countries and others overcome their prejudices against migrants.
If they remain considered a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if host states are able to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through income entry).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global goal: fighting climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary for a similar effort to aim at building a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life and death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
